  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel, entirely unsupervised framework for Grammatical Error Correction (GEC) by repurposing the zero-shot translation capabilities of multilingual sequence-to-sequence models—such as mT5 or NLLB—not through direct fine-tuning or adaptation, but via a new mechanism called 'Intra-Lingual Backtranslation through Zero-Shot Routing' (IB-ZR). The core idea is that when a grammatically flawed sentence in language L is translated through a carefully selected chain of intermediate languages (e.g., L → X → Y → L) using zero-shot translation, the round-trip forces the model to reconstruct the sentence based on deeper semantic coherence and syntactic norms, effectively correcting grammatical errors without ever being trained on error-corrected pairs. We hypothesize that the more structurally divergent the intermediate languages are from L and from each other, the stronger the regularization effect due to increased representational abstraction. For instance, routing an English sentence through Finnish (morphologically complex), Japanese (SOV word order), and Swahili (agglutinative Bantu) before returning to English compels the model to disambiguate and re-synthesize the original intent under diverse grammatical constraints, thereby filtering out ungrammaticality. We further introduce a language-routing strategy optimized for maximum syntactic distance and typological diversity, guided by linguistic databases such as WALS (World Atlas of Language Structures), to maximize the corrective effect. This approach eliminates the need for task-specific training data, synthetic error generation, or architectural modifications. It is particularly impactful for low-resource languages where annotated GEC datasets are scarce. Evaluation will include benchmarking against fine-tuned baselines on standard GEC datasets (e.g., CoNLL-2014, BEA, CGEC) across multiple languages, measuring correction accuracy, fluency, and preservation of meaning. Additionally, we analyze the role of routing length, language typology, and model scale on correction efficacy. By transforming zero-shot translation—a capability originally designed for cross-lingual transfer—into a self-supervised grammatical filter, this work redefines how pre-trained multilingual models can be used for monolingual NLP tasks, opening new avenues for adaptation-free NLP.",
